Calculator
This application is a basic calculator that performs simple arithmetic operations. It has a user-friendly interface that resembles a physical calculator, making it easy to use for individuals of all levels of mathematical expertise.
Key Features:
•	Performs addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division.
•	Accepts decimal numbers.
•	Provides a clear display for entering numbers and viewing results.
•	Offers basic functionality for clearing inputs and negating numbers.
How to Run the Application:
1.	Prerequisites:
o	Ensure you have Java Development Kit (JDK) installed on your system.
o	If not, download it from the official Java website: https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/downloads/
2.	Compilation:
o	Open a terminal or command prompt.
o	Navigate to the directory containing the Calculator.java file.
o	Compile the code using the following command:
Bash
javac Calculator.java
3.	Execution:
o	Once compilation is successful, run the application using:
Bash
java Calculator
Special Instructions:
•	Order of Operations: The calculator follows the standard order of operations (PEMDAS/BODMAS).
•	Division by Zero: Attempting to divide by zero will result in an error message.
•	Clear Button: The "Clear" button clears the entire display, including any pending operations.
•	Delete Button: The "Delete" button removes the last digit entered.
•	Negative Button: The "(-)" button negates the current number in the display.
Additional Notes:
•	The calculator does not support parentheses for grouping operations.
•	It does not provide advanced mathematical functions like trigonometry, logarithms, etc.
